---
const title = "CSS Basics";
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro:components";
---

<Layout title={title}>
  <p>
    Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) is a language used to define the presentation
    and style of HTML.
  </p>
  <hr />
  <h2>Where CSS Resides</h2>
  <p>CSS can reside within three places:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Inline via a style attribute:
      <Code
        code={`<h1 style="color: green">This is a styled header</h1>`}
        lang="html"
      />
    </li>
    <li>
      Within the page within a head tag:
      <Code
        code={`...
<head>
<style>
    h1{
        color: green;
    }
</style>
</head>
...`}
        lang="html"
      />
    </li>
    <li>
      Within the page within a head tag:
      <Code
        code={`...
<head>
    ...
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css" />
</head>
...`}
        lang="html"
      />
    </li>
  </ol>
  <aside>
    In CSS, <strong>"the closest rule wins"</strong>, so the style definition
    closest to the markup is what rules.
  </aside>
  <hr />
  <h2>CSS Selectors</h2>
  <h3>HTML Selectors</h3>
  <p>
    You can use the HTML tag as the selector in your CSS rule. This will apply
    to all tags in the page.
  </p>

  <Code
    code={`<style>
    p{
        background-color: lightblue;
    }
</style>
...
<p>This is a paragraph</p>`}
    lang="html"
  />

  <h3>Class Attribute</h3>
  <p>
    When you need more specificity styling elements that might recur on the
    page.
  </p>

  <Code
    code={`<style>
  .my-style {
    background-color: lightblue;
  }
</style>
...
<p class="my-style">This will have a blue background.</p>
<p>This paragraph won't.</p>`}
    lang="html"
  />

  <h3>Id Attribute</h3>
  <p>Ids are unique to the page--they can only be used once.</p>

  <Code
    code={`<style>
  #my-style {
    background-color: lightblue;
  }
</style>
...
<p id="my-style">This is a paragraph</p>`}
    lang="html"
  />
  <hr />
  <h2>Complex Styles</h2>
  <p>
    CSS3 recently enabled nesting attributes. In the below example, any
    paragraph tag within a div with .my-style will have a padding of 1 rem.
  </p>

  <Code
    code={`<style>
  div.my-style {
    p {
      padding: 1rem;
    }
  }
</style>
...
<div class="my-style">
  <p>This is a paragraph</p>
  <p>This is a another paragraph</p>
</div>
<p>This is a paragraph</p>`}
    lang="html"
  />
  <hr />
  <h2>CSS custom properties</h2>
  <p>
    Unofficially known as CSS variables, this is a common technique to reuse
    values across your stylesheet .
  </p>

  <Code
    code={`<style>
  :root {
    --base-padding: 1em;
    --main-text-color: #333;
  }
  .subhead {
    color: var(--main-text-color);
    padding-left: var(--base-padding);
  }
  .subtext {
    color: var(--main-text-color);
    padding: 0 var(--base-padding);
  }
</style>
...
<h2 class="subhead">This is a subhead</h2>
<p class="subtext">This is subtext.</p>`}
    lang="html"
  />

  <aside class="links">
    <h3>Link:</h3>
    Check out
    <a
      href="https://code.tutsplus.com/tutorials/the-30-css-selectors-you-must-memorize--net-16048"
      >The 30 CSS Selectors You Must Memorize</a
    >
  </aside>

  <h2>CSS Box Model</h2>
