  <hr />
  <h2>Reset</h2>
  <p>
    Not all browsers render the same way which has made it a headache for web
    designers. The open source community has responded, and one way around this
    is by using CSS that helps override the default styling that comes with
    browsers.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href="https://meyerweb.com/eric/tools/css/reset/">Reset CSS</a> - a tool
      created by Eric Meyer in 2007 to assist in making browsers behave the same.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://necolas.github.io/normalize.css/">Normalize.css</a> - in some
      ways a successor to Reset. Makes browser behaviors consistent.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://elad2412.github.io/the-new-css-reset/">New CSS Reset</a>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <hr />
  <h2>System Fonts</h2>
  <p>
    System fonts are fonts that are installed by default on the computer.
    Defining your website to use these fonts saves download time, as the user's
    computer doesn't need to download what's already installed on their machine.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a
        href="https://www.w3schools.com/cssref/css_websafe_fonts.asp"
        target="_blank">CSS Web Safe Font Combinations (W3Schools)</a
      >
    </li>
    <li>
      <a
        href="https://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/system-font-stack/"
        target="_blank">System font stack (CSS-Tricks)</a
      >
    </li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
